Problem and Data Description

This notebook resolves around a Deep Learning problem utilizing the Twitter Tweets Sentiment Dataset. The main idea of the problem is that generally speaking tweets can be categorized into three main sentiments: positive, neutral, and negative. These sentiment refers to the summarized emotion that the poster of said tweet is portraying in his text. For example, a positive tweet could be someone celebrating the birth of a child, while a negative tweet could be a person lamenting the loss of a close family member. On the other hand, a neutral tweet is more or less anything in between that does not majorly sway towards one side or the other.

The data consists of a dataset with 4 columns, and has roughly 27.5k tweets to train with. The columns are:

  • textID - an unique identifier string for each individual tweet
  • text - a string consisting of the text in the tweet
  • selected_text - a string consisting of the main part of the tweet
  • sentiment - a categorical string that describes the sentiment of the tweet

As we are going to use NLP techniques, we must prepare the text data in a way to best suit it. We will do the following to help clean the text:

  1. Splitting the text up into words
  2. Turning the words lowercase
  3. Removing punctuation
  4. Removing @'s which are twitter jargon
  5. Removing leftover numbers
  6. Removing words with accents
  7. Removing stop words and more twitter jargon
  8. Change targets in string to 'product_target' if a target exists
  9. Removing empty strings
  10. Joining all the strings together into one

We will also be mapping integers to our sentiments to aid in the encoding process, with 'positive', 'neutral', and 'negative' becoming 1, 0, and -1 respectively. As the cleaned up version of our 'text' column is sufficient, we will also be dropping the 'selected_text' column as well.

In [123]:
def clean(txt):
    sw = stopwords.words('english')
    sw.extend(['link', 'rt', 'get'])
    punctuation = '!"$%&\'()*+,-./:;<=>?[\\]^_`{|}~!#'
    no_accents_re = re.compile('^[a-z]+$')
    accents = ['', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '', '']
    twitter_re = re.compile('[@][a-zA-Z]*')
    num_re = re.compile('^\d+$')
    
    if isinstance(txt, list):
        t = txt[0].split(' ')
    else:
        t = txt.split(' ')
    t = [w.lower() for w in t]
    t = [w.translate(w.maketrans('','', punctuation)) for w in t]
    t = [w for w in t if not twitter_re.match(w)]
    t = [w for w in t if not num_re.match(w)]
    t = [w for w in t if no_accents_re.match(w)]
    t = [w for w in t if w not in sw]
    if isinstance(txt, list):
        t = ['product_target' if w in product_target(txt[1]) else w for w in t]
        if txt[1].lower() in ['android app', 'ipad or iphone app']:
            t = [w for w in t if w != 'app']
    t = [w for w in t if w]

    return ' '.join(t)


def emotion_label(txt):
    if txt == 'positive':
        return 1
    elif txt == 'neutral':
        return 0
    elif txt == 'negative':
        return -1
    else:
        print('Unknown emotion')

df_cln['txt_f'] = df_cln['text'].apply(clean)
df_cln['sentiment_f'] = df_cln['sentiment'].apply(emotion_label)

The last data preprocessing step will be to tokenize our text. This turns our text data into something that makes more sense for the machine model to read. We will also be OneHotEncoding our sentiment categories as well. While we are at it, we will also split our data into a training set and a validation set.

tokenizer = text.Tokenizer(num_words = 30000, split = ' ')

Model Architecture

As we are undergoing Natural Language Processing tasks in this scenario, the best model architecture for us to use will be Recurrent Neural Networks. This is due to NLP tasks works with not just the individual words but how they fit together as a whole, thus maintaining the context of each text sentence is something that we cannot ignore. RNNs work well in this situation as they are used for handling sequential data, which means it keeps track of the order of individual words as it progresses. RNN is also able to utilize the word embedding we did earlier with the tokenizer which will greatly speed up the learning process.

We will be attempting four different RNN models in this project and testing to see which one provides the best results:

  • SimpleRNN
  • LSTM
  • Bidirectional LSTM
  • GRU

SimpleRNN; a barebones basic model for RNN purposes.

With the results of all of our different models, we can consolidate them to rank them based on our metric of choice. In this case, we will be using the accuracy score on the validation dataset to score each model.

The 6th model ended up with the highest validation accuracy score, and thus will be our model of choice in this scenario. This is the model that had three hyperparameter changes of note, mainly having multiple LSTM layers, multiple Dense layers, as well as having a 'relu' activation function in the hidden layer as well as a 'softmax' activation function for the output layer. The LSTM model was chosen as the performance of all models other than the SimpleRNN were very close to each other, and the other models were all variations of the LSTM so just stuck with LSTM in the end. In addition, the 'softmax' activation function makes perfect sense as it is an activation function that is preferable over the typical 'sigmoid' when there are multiple classes to predict, which in this case is true with our three potential choices for our label.

Conclusion

The result of testing the different models led to our best model being one that consists of multiples of both LSTM and Dense layers. The main takeaway from this project is that simply increasing the number of potential labels from 2 in a binary situation to any greater number will significantly increase the complexity and difficulty in getting accurate predictions. There were two separate ideas that could be helpful to improve performance in case this project needed to be redone, and the first would be to remove the 'neutral' sentiments. While this would greatly lower the amount of data we can work with, depending on the situation it could be beneficial as going back down to two potential labels would greatly improve model performance. As an added bonus, typically 'neutral' sentiment tweets are not as interesting or important as tweets with a 'positive' or 'negative' connotation so could be thrown out without much loss. The second would be to tokenize the words to include multi-word phrases, so instead of having the values of "happy" and "day it would show up as "happy day". While this would exponentially increase the amount of data used for training, it could potentially help capture context in tweets much better than with just single word tokenization.
